<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112794-0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 102413 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
November 27, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 15; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
84 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 DESPERATE WOMEN NEED TO TALK TO YOU by Joan Frank (Conari Press: $9.95; 146 
pp., paperback original). In this collection of columns from various 
periodicals, Joan Frank bemoans the daily life of an aging Baby-Boomer in New 
York: the search for romance, questioning goals, the death of parents, the 
biological timepiece, etc. Her "Girlfriend, I just can't cope" tone is often 
amusing, but many other writers are working the same turf these days, and she 
offers little that's new or insightful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
