 Calendar's pop staff surveys 40 of the nation's most popular or critically 
acclaimed albums : 
</P>
<P>
 ** BONE THUGS-N-HARMONY, "Creepin On Ah Come Up," Ruthless/Relativity. The 
Clevelanders emulate Spice-1's hard-core rap stylings quite capably, and they 
come up with the first successful fusion of gospel and hard-core. 
</P>
<P>
 * 1/2 BOYZ II MEN, "II," Motown. The credits read like a Who's Who of R&B 
songwriters and producers, but the album consists of limp ballads with 
unchallenging lyrics.  
</P>
<P>
 *** SCARFACE, "The Diary," Rap-A Lot/Noo Trybe/Virgin. An aural journey 
through a hard mind flooded with thoughts of funerals, tears, drugs and 
confusion. Unapologetically true to the origins of gangsta rap. 
</P>
