<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY COLLEGE REGIONAL SOCCER PLAYOFFS; ISLAS' GOAL IN OVERTIME LIFTS 
RANCHO SANTIAGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON CLIFFORD, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rancho Santiago's Francisco Islas was kept silent during most of Saturday's 
Southern California men's soccer playoff game against Glendale. 
</P>
<P>
 But Islas didn't let up. 
</P>
<P>
 His persistence paid off with the game-winning goal in the 117th minute, 
giving the Dons a 1-0 victory. 
</P>
<P>
 Islas, who scored nearly half of Rancho Santiago's goals this season, was 
limited to three shots during regulation, and was not a factor during most of 
the overtime period. 
</P>
<P>
 But with three minutes left in overtime, he took a rebound from Andrew Otelie 
on the right side of the net, and banked in the game-winner off the left goal 
post. 
</P>
<P>
 The goal spoiled an outstanding performance by Glendale goalkeeper Erick 
Alvarado, who made 17 saves. 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale had only six shots and Rancho Santiago goalkeeper Scott Zinser didn't 
record a save. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we were hungrier than they were," Rancho Santiago Coach J.P. Frutos 
said. "We were all over them, and we finally executed. I think luck played a 
part in that goal." 
</P>
<P>
 The Dons (17-2-3) dominated the first half, outshooting Glendale, 11-3. Rancho 
Santiago's best scoring opportunity came when Arthur Salce's header hit the 
crossbar at the 25-minute mark. 
</P>
<P>
 The Vaqueros (15-1-5) recovered after halftime, but still found themselves on 
defense most of the second half. 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale's best scoring opportunity came midway through overtime but Giancarlo 
Madariaga's shot on a breakaway went wide left. 
</P>
<P>
 "(Rancho Santiago) deserved to win," Glendale Coach Joe Agoston said. "Our 
game never really developed. We were sloppy in the first half, and settled down 
in the second. I don't think we were mentally ready to win at this level." 
</P>
<P>
 The Dons advance to the State tournament, which will be played Dec. 3-4 in 
Sacramento. 
</P>
</TEXT>
