<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; COUNCIL TO ALLOW ADS ON BUS STOP BENCHES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hoping to maintain bus service and keep fares from skyrocketing, the Simi 
Valley City Council has agreed to alter its sign ordinance to allow advertising 
on bus stop benches. 
</P>
<P>
 The city hopes to raise about $15,000 a year with the advertising. 
</P>
<P>
 In August, the council increased fares from 75 cents to $1, following an 
increase in operating costs and a drop in revenue of as much as 5% on some 
routes. 
</P>
<P>
 The cost to run the four Simi Valley Transit bus lines, which carried 400,000 
riders last year, will be an estimated $1.6 million next year. Operating 
expenses are expected to increase by $83,000 this year, the result of rising 
maintenance, fuel and salary costs. 
</P>
<P>
 Billboard advertising is prohibited in the city. SARA CATANIA 
</P>
